---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AI"
  description="How Ryan Baird uses AI in work, writing, and software development."
  structuredData={{
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    name: "AI",
    url: "https://ryanbaird.com/ai/",
  }}
>
  <section class="section prose">
    <p class="eyebrow">AI</p>
    <h1>AI</h1>
    <p>
      This page is reserved for how I use AI in my work: what I use it for, where I avoid it,
      and how I think about attribution, review, privacy, and responsibility.
    </p>

    <h2>Working Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The default posture is that AI can help draft, explore, refactor, test, summarize, and
      document work, but it does not replace judgment. Code, writing, and decisions still need
      human review before they represent my work.
    </p>

    <h2>Boundaries</h2>
    <p>
      I do not want private, sensitive, or client-confidential material treated as casual model
      input. When AI tools are useful, the inputs and outputs should be appropriate for the
      context and reviewed before use.
    </p>

    <section class="datastar-note" data-signals:details-open="false">
      <button
        class="button secondary"
        type="button"
        data-on:click="$detailsOpen = !$detailsOpen"
        data-attr:aria-expanded="$detailsOpen.toString()"
        aria-controls="ai-detail-note"
        aria-expanded="false"
      >
        Toggle implementation note
      </button>
      <div id="ai-detail-note" data-show="$detailsOpen">
        <p>
          This disclosure uses Datastar attributes for client-side reactivity. The page still
          renders as normal HTML first, and the interaction is a progressive enhancement.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
